---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import LessonShell from "../../components/LessonShell.astro";
import Reveal from "../../components/Reveal.astro";
import { LESSONS } from "../../data/curriculum";

const lesson = LESSONS.find((l) => l.id === "concept-mcp")!;
---

<Layout title={`${lesson.title} · Learn AI`} description={lesson.blurb} currentId="concept-mcp">
    <LessonShell lesson={lesson}>
      <p>
        <strong>MCP</strong> (Model Context Protocol) is a standard for letting an AI assistant <em>reach
        into the rest of your stack</em> — your filesystem, your Slack, your Linear board, your database,
        your browser. Without MCP, the AI only knows what's in the current chat. With MCP, it can read
        a real-time spreadsheet, post to Slack, search Postgres, or click around a webpage.
      </p>

      <div class="mcp-pic">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 600 280" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" aria-label="MCP hub-and-spoke diagram">
          <!-- AI client in center -->
          <rect x="240" y="120" width="120" height="40" rx="8" fill="currentColor"/>
          <text x="300" y="146" font-family="Inter, sans-serif" font-size="13" fill="var(--bg)" text-anchor="middle" font-weight="600">AI client</text>
          <text x="300" y="180" font-family="Inter, sans-serif" font-size="10" fill="currentColor" opacity="0.7" text-anchor="middle">Claude Code · Cursor · Continue</text>

          <!-- MCP servers around -->
          <g font-family="Inter, sans-serif" font-size="11" fill="currentColor">
            <rect x="40"  y="20" width="120" height="36" rx="6" fill="var(--surface)" stroke="var(--line-strong)"/>
            <text x="100" y="42" text-anchor="middle">Filesystem</text>

            <rect x="220" y="20" width="120" height="36" rx="6" fill="var(--surface)" stroke="var(--line-strong)"/>
            <text x="280" y="42" text-anchor="middle">GitHub</text>

            <rect x="400" y="20" width="120" height="36" rx="6" fill="var(--surface)" stroke="var(--line-strong)"/>
            <text x="460" y="42" text-anchor="middle">Slack</text>

            <rect x="20"  y="220" width="120" height="36" rx="6" fill="var(--surface)" stroke="var(--line-strong)"/>
            <text x="80"  y="242" text-anchor="middle">Postgres</text>

            <rect x="220" y="220" width="120" height="36" rx="6" fill="var(--surface)" stroke="var(--line-strong)"/>
            <text x="280" y="242" text-anchor="middle">Linear / Jira</text>

            <rect x="420" y="220" width="120" height="36" rx="6" fill="var(--surface)" stroke="var(--line-strong)"/>
            <text x="480" y="242" text-anchor="middle">Browser / Playwright</text>
          </g>

          <!-- Connecting lines -->
          <g stroke="#cc5500" stroke-width="1.2" fill="none">
            <line x1="100" y1="56"  x2="270" y2="120"/>
            <line x1="280" y1="56"  x2="300" y2="120"/>
            <line x1="460" y1="56"  x2="330" y2="120"/>
            <line x1="80"  y1="220" x2="270" y2="160"/>
            <line x1="280" y1="220" x2="300" y2="160"/>
            <line x1="480" y1="220" x2="330" y2="160"/>
          </g>

          <text x="300" y="265" font-family="Inter, sans-serif" font-size="10" fill="currentColor" opacity="0.6" text-anchor="middle">MCP servers — installed locally or hosted</text>
        </svg>
      </div>

      <h2>The 30-second mental model</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>An <strong>MCP server</strong> exposes a set of tools (e.g. "read file", "post message", "run SQL").</li>
        <li>An <strong>MCP client</strong> is your AI tool (Claude Code, Cursor, Continue, etc.) that knows how to call those tools.</li>
        <li>You install the server, configure the client to find it, restart, and now your AI can use it.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What people actually use it for</h2>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>MCP server</th><th>What it unlocks</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Filesystem</td><td>"Summarise all PDFs in ~/Downloads"</td></tr>
          <tr><td>GitHub</td><td>"Open a PR for this branch with a good description"</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Slack</td><td>"Post the deploy result to #ops"</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Postgres / SQLite</td><td>"How many active users last week?"</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Linear / Jira / Asana</td><td>"What's blocked in my queue?"</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Playwright / browser</td><td>"Click around the staging site and report any 500s"</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Google Drive / Notion</td><td>"Update the spec doc with these decisions"</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>Setup pattern (the same for almost any MCP)</h2>
      <ol class="steps">
        <li>Find the MCP server. Most are at <a href="https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/servers" target="_blank" rel="noopener">github.com/modelcontextprotocol/servers</a> or as npm/pypi packages.</li>
        <li>Add it to your AI client's MCP config. In Claude Code: <code class="inline">claude mcp add &lt;name&gt; &lt;command&gt;</code>. In Cursor: <em>Settings → MCP → Add</em>.</li>
        <li>Restart the client.</li>
        <li>Ask the AI: "What MCP tools do you have?" — it'll list them.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>Why it's a big deal.</strong> Before MCP, every AI tool had its own incompatible plugin
        system. With MCP, write a server once, use it from any client. The list of available servers
        grows by the week.
      </div>

      <h2>Where MCP shows up in this tutorial</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Coding CLIs (Claude Code, Cursor, Continue) — primary clients.</li>
        <li>Open-source agents (Hermes, OpenClaw, Goose) — most support MCP.</li>
        <li>Chat apps — partial support, growing. Claude.ai supports remote MCP in some plans.</li>
      </ul>

      <Reveal q="Who made MCP?">
        Anthropic open-sourced the spec in late 2024. OpenAI, Google, Microsoft, and the major editor
        vendors adopted it through 2025/26. It's a community standard now, governed openly.
      </Reveal>
      <Reveal q="Are MCP servers safe?">
        A server runs on your machine (or wherever you put it) and has whatever access you give it.
        Treat third-party MCP servers like any code: prefer the official ones from
        <a href="https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/servers" target="_blank" rel="noopener">modelcontextprotocol/servers</a>,
        scope credentials tightly, read the code for anything that touches sensitive data.
      </Reveal>
      <Reveal q="Can I write my own MCP server?">
        Yes — there are SDKs in TypeScript, Python, Go, Rust, Kotlin, C#. A trivial server is ~40 lines.
        See <a href="https://modelcontextprotocol.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener">modelcontextprotocol.io</a>.
      </Reveal>
    </LessonShell>
</Layout>

<style>
  .mcp-pic {
    background: var(--surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    padding: 0.6rem 1rem;
    margin: 1.2rem 0;
  }
  .mcp-pic svg { width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }
</style>
